  :prose
"Conway's Game of Life has been studied for fifty years, and the
catalog of interesting patterns is thousands of entries. This
appendix picks the essential ones — the patterns every Life
practitioner should know.

There are four broad classes:

- **Still lifes**: shapes that don't change from generation to
  generation.
- **Oscillators**: shapes that cycle through a period of N
  generations and return to themselves.
- **Spaceships**: shapes that translate across the grid, moving
  their position each period.
- **Guns and breeders**: shapes that emit spaceships forever, growing
  the live-cell count without bound.

Each entry gives the pattern's name, size, spawn call, and a
one-line description.

---

## E.1 Still lifes (period 1)

**Block** — 2x2 square. Simplest still life.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'block 5 5)
```

**Beehive** — six cells in a hexagonal shape. Very common in random
soups.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'beehive 10 10)
```

**Loaf** — seven cells resembling a bread loaf. Also common in
random soups.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'loaf 15 5)
```

**Boat** — five cells, asymmetric still life.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'boat 20 5)
```

**Ship** — six cells, asymmetric.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'ship 25 5)
```

**Tub** — four cells in a diamond shape with a hole. Rare.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'tub 30 5)
```

## E.2 Oscillators

**Blinker** (period 2) — three cells in a row that alternates between
horizontal and vertical.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'blinker 5 15)
```

**Toad** (period 2) — two rows of three cells, offset by one column.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'toad 10 15)
```

**Beacon** (period 2) — two blocks touching diagonally.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'beacon 15 15)
```

**Pulsar** (period 3) — large, symmetric, beautiful. 48-cell max
population.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'pulsar 20 15)
```

**Pentadecathlon** (period 15) — long thin shape that oscillates in a
15-generation cycle.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'pentadecathlon 35 15)
```

**Kok's galaxy** (period 8) — large symmetric oscillator.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'koks-galaxy 5 25)
```

## E.3 Spaceships

**Glider** — 5 cells, moves diagonally one square every 4 generations.
The most famous Life pattern. If you spawn nothing else, spawn a
glider.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'glider 5 30)
```

**Lightweight spaceship (LWSS)** — 9 cells, moves horizontally one
square every 4 generations. Faster than a glider (moves 2 diagonal
distances per 4 generations vs 1 for the glider).

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'lwss 15 30)
```

**Middleweight spaceship (MWSS)** — 11 cells, similar behavior to
LWSS but larger.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'mwss 30 30)
```

**Heavyweight spaceship (HWSS)** — 13 cells.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'hwss 45 30)
```

**Copperhead** (period 10) — a modern discovery (2016), 28-cell
spaceship moving 1 cell every 10 generations.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'copperhead 5 40)
```

## E.4 Guns

**Gosper glider gun** — 36 cells; emits a glider every 30 generations
forever. The first pattern discovered that grows the live-cell count
unboundedly.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'gosper-glider-gun 5 5)
```

**Simkin glider gun** — smaller than Gosper, period 100.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'simkin-glider-gun 25 25)
```

## E.5 Breeders (multi-tier growth)

**Simple breeder** — emits guns which emit gliders. Live-cell count
grows quadratically with time. Requires ~500x500 grid to observe
long-term.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'switch-engine-breeder 30 30)
```

## E.6 Puffers and rakes

**Puffer** — a pattern that moves and leaves debris behind. Live-cell
count grows linearly.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'noahs-ark-puffer 20 60)
```

**Rake** — a puffer whose debris is spaceships. So it's a moving
gun.

## E.7 Methuselahs — small patterns with long, complex evolution

**R-pentomino** — 5 cells. Runs for 1103 generations before
stabilizing.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'r-pentomino 40 40)
```

**Acorn** — 7 cells. Runs for 5206 generations, produces 633 live
cells at stabilization including 13 gliders.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'acorn 45 45)
```

**Diehard** — 7 cells that die after exactly 130 generations. Named
because it holds on remarkably long for such a tiny start.

```scheme
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'diehard 50 45)
```

## E.8 Compositions

Life has been shown to be computationally universal — you can build
a Turing machine out of Life patterns. It has also been shown to
implement itself (a Life pattern that simulates Life). These are
enormous constructions using millions of cells, but they exist.

At the small scale, you can compose:

```scheme
;; Gun that fires gliders at a block. The block absorbs.
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'gosper-glider-gun 5 5)
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'block             45 40)
```

```scheme
;; Two guns pointed at each other; gliders collide, sometimes into
;; other patterns.
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'gosper-glider-gun 5  5)
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'gosper-glider-gun 65 5 :mirrored #t)
```

## E.9 Non-Life rules with famous patterns

**HighLife (B36/S23)**: has a replicator, a 12-cell pattern that
grows into two copies of itself, then four, then eight...

```scheme
(canvas-rule-set! 'B36/S23)
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'highlife-replicator 30 30)
```

**Day and Night (B3678/S34678)**: symmetric under swap of alive and
dead cells. Complex patterns emerge with different structure than
Life.

**Seeds (B2/S)**: nothing survives; every alive cell dies in the next
generation. Alive cells only appear from births.

```scheme
(canvas-rule-set! 'B2/S)
(canvas-spawn-pattern 'random 0.05)
```

## E.10 Building your own catalog

Every rule has its own catalog waiting to be discovered. When you
invent a rule, run it from random soup for 10000 generations. Note
what survives. Spawn each survivor at position (0,0) and see if it
oscillates, translates, or grows.

The runtime can help with this: give her a rule and a soup density, and
she'll run 100 trials in the background, cluster the outcomes by
final live-cell pattern, and report the most-common survivors.

Related:
- Chapter 8: cellular automata in detail
- Appendix J: emergent case studies
- Chapter 15: cellular-automaton-like grass rules")
